did.abstract: The records consist of videotapes, topical files, and other materials from the production, Rights and Wrongs , a weekly news magazine that ran from 1993 to 1996 and concerned global human rights issues.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Purchased from The International Center for Global Communications Foundation by the Yale University Library and transferred to Manuscripts and Archives, 2003.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Series I to III are unprocessed and may contain sensitive information or be in a physical state that would prohibit use. Researchers wishing to request access should email mssa.assist@yale.edu requesting specific box numbers in order to initiate the review process, which may take several weeks.

Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist must pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository. Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy for their personal use should consult Copying Services information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Copyright has been transferred to Yale University for materials authored or otherwise produced by the creator(s) of this collection. Copyright status for other collection materials is unknown. Transmission or reproduction of materials protected by U.S. Copyright Law (Title 17, U.S.C.) beyond that allowed by fair use requires the written permission of the copyright owners. Works not in the public domain cannot be commercially exploited without permission of the copyright owners. Responsibility for any use rests exclusively with the user.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Descriptions of the programs were provided by the creator.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The records consist of videotapes, topical files, and other materials from the production, Rights and Wrongs , a weekly news magazine that ran from 1993 to 1996 and concerned global human rights issues.
Series IV, Programs, consists of the programs as aired.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged in four series: Series I. Camera Originals, 1993-1996; Series II. Stock Footage, 1993-1996; Series III. Paper Files, 1993-1996; Series IV. Programs, 1993-1996.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Rights and Wrongs was a weekly television news magazine that ran from 1993 to 1996 and concerned global human rights issues. The program was hosted by Charlayne Hunter-Gault and was broadcast on 85 public television stations and in 35 foreign countries.

arrangement.p: The series is arranged by creator assigned tape number.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists segments on human rights activists and the United Nations (UN) Declaration of Human Rights; Haitian refugees held by the United States Government at Guantanamo Bay; 'Video Diaries' from the Palestinian occupied territories; the Witness Program of the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights distributiion of video cameras to human rights activists around the world; the UN's Truth Commission on El Salvador; and an interview with Elliott Abrams, Reagan State Department official.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the pros and cons of humanitarian military interventions and their impact on human rights; inteviews from Somalia, Sudan, Liberia, and Rwanda; reports from Tajikistan, Iraq, and South Africa; and a profile of a human rights activist in Zaire and his NGO's work to end decades of dictatorial rule.

did.unittitle: When Will War Crimes be Punished?

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program includes segments on the UN War Crimes Tribunal's plan to deal with the atrocities committed in the former Yugoslavia; interviews with Aryen Naler of Human Rights Watch and Feryal Gharahi of Equality Now, a women's group that supports rape victims in Bosnia; Susan Sarandon reading a letter from a Haitian woman being held at Guantanamo, a United States holding station for many refugees; Chris Hani, a murdered South African activist, is remembered; Poland celebrates the fiftieth anniversary of the Warsaw ghetto; and a music video of a Croatian alternative Balkan musician Nenad Bach sings about tolerance.

did.unittitle: Truth As a Casualty of War

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on selections from Academy Award winning documentary The Panama Deception ; interviews with Barbara Trent, Panama's UN Ambassador, and Jose Marin of the Center for Constitutional Rights; a debate on media restrictions on war coverage with John D. McArthur, Jr., publisher of Harper's Weekly , and Colonel Charles Ricks of the US Defense Department; a report on the Gay Pride March in Washington D.C., and on Kashmir and Chad; and a Music video featuring a Haitian band, Boukman Eksperians, which sings for human rights.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists on segments on the rise of Hungary's fascist hate groups targeting Jews and Gypsies; an interview with philanthropist George Soros, who discusses his human rights work in Eastern Europe; reports on medical relief for Cuba, anti-war activists in Belgrade, Serbia, and human rights heroes being honored in Washington, DC; and excerpts films from the Human Rights Watch Film Festival.

did.unittitle: The First Hundred Days of the Clinton Administration

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on Clinton's human rights policies; an interview with former US President, Jimmy Carter; and reports from Sarajevo, Sri Lanka, and Bombay, India.

did.unittitle: Rape as a Weapon of War

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on rape as a conscious strategy of war in conflicts such as Bosnia, Kashmir, and Iraq; an interview with Charlotte Bunch from the Center of Women's Global Leadership; reports on Tibetan refugees in India, on Guatemala, and on Joan Baez's visit to Sarajevo; and a music video of Sweet Honey in the Rock singing about women's rights.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of "Escape from China," a secretly filmed profile of one of the Tiananmen Square uprising's young leaders and an analysis of the controversy over China's "Most Favored Nation" status as a United States trading partner.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on a video by SAGA, a Sarajevo-based group of film makers, from inside the besieged Bosnian capital; coverage of the New York Times , described as "part news, part horror movie"; a report on Prague's neo-Nazi skinheads; reports on distribution of cameras to human rights activists, on environmental protection in Haiti and Brazil, and on Kosovo; and a music video showing musicians gathering at a Sarajevo monument to bring world attention to the crisis in Bosnia.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the problems, priorities, and players at the 1993 United Nations World Human Rights Conference, the first to be held in 25 years; interviews with high-ranking UN officials, with US Undersecretary of State Timothy Worth, and President Jimmy Carter; UN Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali talks about the limitations of universality and the current status and future of the UN; families of murder victims tour the United States to combat the death penalty; Cambodia moves towards democracy; and a human rights advocate becomes president in Guatemala.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Program consists of segments on the resistance of ethnic Albanians against Serbian occupation; Guantanamo Bay as a prison camp for Haitians; a report on El Salvador; and a discussion of United States immigration policy with Arthur Helton of the Lawyers Committee for Human rights.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Program consists of interviews with UN officials, government delegates, NGO representatives and activists; reports on Angola, Egypt, and Liberia; and a musical salute to Nelson Mandela.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of efforts to treat female circumcision as a human rights abuse; Pulitzer Prize-winning author Alice Walker discusses Possessing the Secret of Joy , her novel about an African woman who responds to this cultural tradition; Diary From Hell about Manila's Smokey Mountain garbage dump, makes a link between the environment and human rights; and human rights award is given to a daily newspaper in Sarajevo.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of a video diary from Nogorno-Karabakh, an Armenian Christian enclave surrounded by the largely Muslim former Soviet Republic of Azeraijan; reports on Cambodia and Guatemala; report from inside Serbia, about a largely Muslim enclave that, until recently, was free from the horrors of "ethnic cleansing"; and a music video of Luis de la Guerra singing "El Costa de la Vida."

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on "Papakolea: a story of Hawaiian Land" that examines homesteads, their impact on Native Hawaiian culture and heritage, and the struggle to preserve what land still remains; the discovery of gold and how the methods of its extraction threatens the lives and culture of the T'boli people of the Philippines; and Indigenous peoples from around the world perform at the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the impact of the North Atlantic Free Trade Agreement and the United States Industry's search for cheaper labor and manufacturing costs on health, the environment, labor, and civil liberties; a Sarajevo "Video Diary" and a report on the Tamil Tiger guerrillas in Sri Lanka; and a report on human rights abuses against illegal immigrants at the United States/Mexico border.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of highlights from films produced by SAGA (Sarajevo Group of Artists) and Director Ademir Kenovic offering a chilling look of the everyday life in a city under siege.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on SAGA's films about daily life in Sarajevo; a commentary by the Pulitzer Prize-winning New York Times correspondent John Burns; and American writer Susan Sontag stages Samuel Beckett's "Waiting for Godot" in Sarajevo and discusses its current relevance to the current situation there.

did.unittitle: Whatever Happened to the War Crimes Tribunal?

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Program consists of segments on UN Security Council war crimes tribunal to examine crimes against humanity in Bosnia/Herzegovina and other former Yugoslav republics; Rights & Wrongs asks "Why?" one year later no investigations are underway; an interview with United States human rights expert, Mort Halperin; home video footage from Angola's frontlines; a commentary by Andrew Tyndall on why the television networks have ignored Mexico in their coverage of the NAFTA debate; ands an exclusive interview with Jim Sheridan, director of In the Name of the Father .

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on an examination of the conflict in Northern Ireland and its impact on issues including jobs, housing, and the vote; a commentary by Andrew Tyndall on why the networks are more interested in the troubles of the House of Windsor than the troubles in Northern Ireland; a exclusive interview with Bernadette Devlin McAliskey; and reports from Sarajevo with a commentary by Pulitzer Prize-winning New York Times reporter John Burns.

did.unittitle: South Africa: a Human Rights Success Story

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of a report on politically inspired violence threatening the transition to a multi-racial democracy; an interview with Judge Richard Goldstone, the head of the judicial commission, which revealed a conspiracy at senior levels of South Africa's security forces to sabotage the transition to majority rule; excerpts from Mama Awethu , a film by Bethany Yarrow about women in South Africa; and a music video of a multi-racial group singing "Freedom Charter," a song about the struggle to end apartheid.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on Reverend Beyers Naude, a remarkable Afrikaner, once part of the apartheid establishment, who now speaks publicly against it; an interview with Kenyan human rights activist Wangari Maathai, with a rebuttal from Kenyan Ambassador Don Nanjira; a report from Rwanda with representatives from African Rights and Amnesty International; and excerpts from features and documentaries from the Human Rights Watch Film Festival.

did.unittitle: The United Nations and Human Rights

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the status of the UN's human rights mandate in light of its Peacekeeping Operations in Bosnia, Somalia, and El Salvador; an interview with Kofi Annan, Under-Secretary-General of UN Peacekeeping Operations; an interview with Anna Deavere Smith, writer, performer, social commentator, and star of her own one woman show, "Twilight: Los Angeles 1992"; Hungary's nationalist movement; and the Black Audio Film Collective's examination of Black and Afro-Caribbean experience in the United Kingdom.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on "the human rights crisis in Myanmar", an examination of the documented human rights abuses by the State Law and Order Restoration Council (SLORC); an interview with Kenneth Roth, Executive Director of Human Rights Watch, about ethnic warfare, new ways to link trade and human rights, and how the Clinton Administration is viewed by human rights activists; a look inside New York City's El Puente Academy of Peace and Justice; and music video of Romanian musicians singing about revolution.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on President Nelson Mandela discussing his plan to forge a "government of national unity" in South Africa; the controversy surrounding the linking of trade to human rights policy, particularly with regard to China's "Most Favored Nation" status, with comments by Henry Kissinger, Lane Kirkland, the Dalai Lama, US Assistant Secretary of State for Human Rights John Shattuck, and former Chinese political prisoner Wang Juntao; and excerpts from " Satya: a Prayer for the Enemy ," a film which explores the spiritual resistance of Tibetan nuns persecuted by their Chinese occupiers.

did.unittitle: Human Rights in the Occupied Territories

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the tranisition to Palestinian self-rule in parts of the Israeli-occupied territories; efforts of field workers from two different but complementary human rights groups--one Palestinian, the other Israeli; an interview with Hanan Ashrawi, one time Palestinian peace negotiator and head of a Palestinian human rights group; Allen Ginsberg reading his newest poem, "Peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina"; and a music video of Yothu Yindi, a predominantly aboriginal band of musicians from Australia

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the lack of media independence in post-communist Hungary where broadcast media came under attack by the government for its "liberal bias"; commentary by Andrew Tyndall on how the media covers itself; the growing number of journalists who are killed while on assignment; the world's most unusual radio station, Belgrade's B-92, which mixes music with anti-war activism in Serbia's Capital.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the political situation in Haiti; an nterview with exiled Haitian President Jean Bertrand Aristide; highlights form David Korb's film, The Other Haiti , about grass roots democratic movements there; Andrew Tyndall on television news coverage of Haiti; and the Haitian peasant democracy movement and its music.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the conditions of children around the world; a rap video written and performed by students at El Puente Academy for Peace and Justice, in Brooklyn; a rofile of a 13 year old African-American boy who lives in Washington, DC; a profile of a 15 year old girl in India; the recent brutality against Brazilian street children; Andrew Tyndall on television news coverage of children and human rights; and Judy Collins' song, I Dream of Peace, accompanied by drawings and writings of children living with war.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on Mississippi's "Freedom Summer," when the civil rights struggle for the right of African Americans to vote brought worldwide attention to human rights abuses in the United States; Canada's hydroelectric project at James Bay spawns conflict between indigenous peoples and the state-owned energy company; the US Army's School of the Americas in Georgia trains soldiers, some of whom have become Latin America's worst dictators; Andrew Tyndall on the United States media's coverage of Native Americans; Haile Germia's feature film, Sankofa , offers a new view of slavery in America; and the director talks about his work and the difficulty of making such a film.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on an examination of Thailand's burgeoning, multi-billion dollar, sex industry and the sexual trafficking of minors; an exerpt form the film, Cuba Va , shows the diversity of opinion held by Cuban youths about the Revolution; Nobel Peace Prize winner Rigoberta Menchu, who fights for the rights of indigenous people in Guatemanla and around the world ; and the impact of American Rap and Rock and Roll on the Cuban music scene

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the former Soviet Republic of Tajikistan, where the civil war has taken an estimanted 50,000 lives and has resulted in summary execution, disappearances, and ethnic strife; Father Ricardo Rezende and his work defending poor, landless peasants in the Brazilian Amazon; Peacewatch, an ongoing chronicle of the global effort to define peacemanking an to examine the interplay of conflict resolution and human rights; forced labor in Burma; the International Gay and Lesbian Human Rights Awards; and excerpts form Chelyabinsk: The Most Contaminated Spot on the Planet , and an interview with Slawomir Grunberg on the relationship between human rights and the environment.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on Los Angeles' attempts to promote tolerance; an interview with controversial author and philosopher Cornel West; a profile of human rights hero and children's conflict resolution educator Darryl Williams, who was paralyzed by a sniper's bullet during Boston's 1979 busing crisis.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on Geoffrey Canada directing Harlem's Rheedlen Centers for Children & Families which provides quality preventive social services to New York City's most devastated communities; an Appalachian youth and former skinhead talking about how his life was turned around by a group called Appalshop; and an interview with Marian Wright Edelman, Founder and Director of the Children's Defense Fund.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on filmmaker Geoffrey O'Connor's Academy Award-nominated story of the Waiapi people of Brazil, At the Edge of Conflict , which offers an inside look at the struggle of indigenous people and their leader, Chief Wai-Wai, to survive the encroachment of developers and regain legal title to their traditional lands; and Indigenous peoples around the world fight for land rights.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program marks the anniversary of Nelson Mandela's 1994 election with segments on an American/South African co-production, Countdown to Freedom: Ten Days that Changed South Africa , narrated by James Earl Jones and Alfre Woodard; an interview with Dr. Makaziwe Mandela, President Mandela's eldest daughter and the University of Witswatersrand's advisor on Affirmative Action/Equal Opportunity; return to Robben Islan Prison - 1200 former prisoners join together at this Cape Town prison for a reunion; and a music Video with Rap group, Prophets of the City, singing "Never Again".

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on The Carpet , a documentary film by Swedish director Magnus Bergmar that looks at Pakistan's system of child labor and the movement to abolish it; an update on the short life and tragic death of Iqbal Masih, featuring footage from his funeral and charges that his death was part of a conspiracy against him by Pakistan's carpet "mafia", and an interview with UNICEF Deputy Executive Director Guido Bertolaso

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segment on what has happened since the genocide violence in Rwanda; a Rwandan wedding ceremony: the birth of a new family facilities the healing of a community; and an interview with Ken Roth, Executive Director of Human Rights Watch, on the impact war crimes tribunals have had in Rwanda and around the world.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on Moving the Mountain , directed by Michael Apted and produced by Trudie Styler; an interview with Li Lu, a former student leader, now living in exile, on the decline of human rights in China; and From Hollywood to Hanoi , where Vietnamese-American filmmaker journeys back to Vietnam to understand her own feelings about the war. She visits My Lai, the site of a massacre by American troops, to make an appeal for reconciliation and friendship.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on an interview with US Under Secretary of State Peter Tarnoff, Washington's top negotiator, and Edgardo Valdes, a representative of the Cuban Government at the United Nations, on the nature of the changing US-Cuban relations, and its impact on human rights; Emmy Award-winning film maker Hon Alpert, reports from Cuba on the state of Cuba and Cuban-American relations form the vantage point of ordinary Cubans; and an interview with two Cuban-Americans, Frank Calzon of Freedom House (a long time critic of Castro's policies) and Sam Farber, writer for the Campaign for Peace & Democracy about their opposing positions on the United States embargo.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on Algerian conflict between an authoritarian government and an insurgent Islamist movement; independent producer Susan Mazur, going behind the lines in Kashmir to report on the conflict's mounting death toll and its human rights implications; children's impressions of the war in Sarejevo, produced by Ademir Kenovic and the SAGA film company; and women under Islamic law speaking out and calling for an end to second class citizenship.

did.unittitle: The Yellow Wasps: Roots of Ethnic Cleansing [part I]

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of an extended excerpt from the documentray Yellow Wasps , directed by Ilan Ziv and produced by Rory O'Connor, examines ethnic cleansing in the former Yugoslavia through a war crimes trial of a Serbian para-military group called "Yellow Wasps" and jounalists and survivors relating their personal experiences.

did.unittitle: The Yellow Wasps: Roots of Ethnic Cleansing [part II]

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program examines the discovery of concentration camps and response of the international community; and Charlayne Hunter-Gault questions former U.S. Secretary of State, Lawrence Eagleburger, on the moral implications of non-intervention

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of Jonathan Mann, architect of the World Health Organization's program on AIDS, exploring the connection between health and human rights; and an interview with Yale Law School's Prof. Harlan Dalton and Prof. Karen Porter, who teaches law and medicine at Washington University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on "Tomorrow's Leaders" conference held in Venice, Italy, and sponsored by Nobel Laureate, Elie Wiesel, where young people from Northern Ireland, the former Yugoslavia, Africa, the Middle East and the United States, join seasoned foreign diplomats in discussion about tolerance, dialogue and negotiations; an interview with Holocaust survivor Elie Wiesel on the importance of dialogue; and PS 230 in Brooklyn, New York, an elementary school where students learn conflict resolution techinques in an effort to prevent violence and promote tolerance.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the Centers for Victims of Torture in Minneapolis, MN and in Toronto, Canada; Are We the Enemy?, a report on how an estimated 8 to 10 million active land mines are affecting the lives of Cambodians who, because of these mines, have the highest number of handicapped people per capita in the world, produced by the Women's Media Centre of Cambodia and Media Ties Inc; and New Technologies, a report on how human rights groups like Amnesty, HR Watch and Peacenet/IGC are using computers, CD-Rom's and the Internet to link up worldwide.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of nine-time Emmy Award winning journalist Jon Alpert traveling to China's Fujian province, where people agree to pay more than $30,000 to smugglers, or 'snakeheads,' who will sneak them into the United States. Once in the US many of these immigrants face long stays in INS detention, an inability to find work, except in sweatshops, illegally low pay and horrid living conditions. Includes an interview with refugee expert, Arthur Helton and award-winning journalist, Ying Chan, about the issue.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the ongoing conflict in Russia, with comment from Sergei Kovalev, Russia's former commissioner of Human Rights, and Ludmilla Thorne, a human rights specialist at Freedom House; Thomas Goltz's "video diary" about the village of Somashki and its efforts to defend itself from the Russian army's assault; and an exclusive interview with Fred Cuny, a disaster relief specialist and human rights hero who traveled to Chechnya in 1995 and has been missing and presumed dead ever since.

did.unittitle: Israel and Palestine: At the Edge of Peace?

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on a Palestinian living in a refugee camp and an Israeli settler living a few miles away, who taped "video diaries" recording their perspectives on the ongoing peace process in the Middle East from 1993 to 1996; and an interview with Terje Larsen, whose creative peacemaking role and spectacular results led to his appointment as Undersecretary-General to the United Nations and Special Coordinator in the Occupied Territories.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the media's shrinking coverage of international news and its impact on human rights with an interview with media analyst Noam Chomsky and a look at the role of new tools and technologies--low cost video cameras, computers, and the internet--in human rights activism, a phenomenon which some have termed "weapons of mass communication."

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on institutions like the United Nations, the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund, and NATO in a post-Cold War context; the World Bank activities in Mexico and their impact on the daily lives of ordinary Mexican citizens; and an interview with UN Assistant Secretary General Alvaro de Soto.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on women's rights globally and within the United States; feminist/activist Bella Abzug reflecting on the growing empowerment of non-governmental organizations and the strategies that made the outcome of the Beijing Conference so successful; three grassroots organizers from Bangladesh, Zimbabwe, and the United States discussing their work and how women's issues are linked globally; and an interview with Vandana Shiva, an Indian environmentalist and women's activist.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Safe Havens programs examine the fall of Srebrenica, a town in Bosnia declard a "safe have" under UN protection and ccontain interviews with former State Department Ambassador at Large, Robert Gallucci, and Newsday correspondent and Pulitzer Prize winner, Roy Gutman, about the lessons of the fall of Srebrenica.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Safe Havens programs examine the fall of Srebrenica, a town in Bosnia declard a "safe have" under UN protection and ccontain interviews with former State Department Ambassador at Large, Robert Gallucci, and Newsday correspondent and Pulitzer Prize winner, Roy Gutman, about the lessons of the fall of Srebrenica.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of excerpts on Leap of Faith , a documentary about segregated Northern Ireland, where parents have created an integrated school of Catholics and Protestants to begin the process of religious and political reconciliation; Seeds of Peace , a documentary focusing on a unique summer camp in Maine, where young Israelis and Palestinians learn to understand each other and resolve differences constructively; and an interview with Archishop Desmond Tutu about South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission, its mandate to expose the crimes of apartheid and to promote reconciliation in a long-divided South Africa.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on the "STAND FOR CHILDREN' rally, where hundreds of thousands of Americans and children's rights advocates gathered in Washington, DC; the Denmark Children's Council, one of the first attempts to bring the voice of children directly into the seat of government; and Yasmin, a street child from India, showing her world and the importance of education through her personal video diary.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segments on At the Edge of the Conflict " featuring Chief Wai-Wai of the Waiapi people, who fought for and won land rights for indigenous people in the Amazon jungle of Brazil; Guatemalan Nobel Laureate Rigoberta Menchu, an advocate for Indigenous and women's rights. *Journalist Roy Gutman and documentary filmmaker Ademir Kenovic chronicle the war in the former Yugoslavia; the memorial to Veronica Guerin, a journalist killed while covering the war in Ireland; a profile of Richard N'Sanzabagoma, a human rights activist in Rwanda; a profile of Geoffrey Canada, who defends the rights of children in Harlem, New York; and a conversation with Elie Wiesel, Nobel Peace Prize recipient.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of reports on the human rights situation in Nigeria, focusing on the elections aborted by the military regime, the role of the US government and Shell Oil, the execution of a prominent human rights activist, and the worldwide response to the situation; lobbying efforts in the US by various American corporations, non-profit organizations, Nigerian nationals, and the American public; and an excerpt from "Ken Saro-Wiwa: an African Martyr," the final interview with the Nigerian human rights activist who fought for the Ogoni people and an end to the oppressive and illegal regime ruling Nigeria.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The program consists of segment on United States corporations and their use of child labor and how consumers and public opinion can change these practices; excerpts from My Life is Mine , a documentary about the life of a child worker in Pakistan's brick kiln industry; and Bob Herbert, New York Times columnist, discussing the response of American corporations to the public outcry against child labor.
